@Sjors I'm using a wide range of tools of which some are open source, some are commercial and some are homegrown. I've written my own infrastructure for handling/normalising/triaging the results from these tools.

But generally I would recommend simply starting with what Clang provides: `clang-tidy` and the Clang Static Analyser. That will give the most bang for the buck to start with :-)

@fanquake's notes in https://github.com/fanquake/core-review/blob/master/clang-tools.md seems like a good start.
